{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"64fb352a-4cf6-46d6-a641-b5d115542268","content":"**Use `dotnet-trace`** — it's the simplest option for .NET 8 CPU profiling.\n\n### Quick steps:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install (one-time)\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or **PerfView**.\n\n### Alternative: PerfView (deeper analysis)\n\nIf you need kernel-level CPU stacks (e.g., native code, I/O waits):\n\n```powershell\n# Download from https://github.com/microsoft/perfview/releases\nPerfView.exe collect -Duration:30 -Zip:true\n```\n\nPerfView gives richer data (thread time, kernel stacks) but has a steeper learning curve.\n\n**Recommendation:** Start with `dotnet-trace` for managed-code hot paths. Escalate to PerfView if the CPU time is spent in native/OS code.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2dc384a7-ef1c-4a9a-91e5-f66ee7cca5a1","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task. I should give a concise, practical answer.\n\nThe best tool for this scenario is `dotnet-trace` or PerfView. For CPU profiling specifically, `dotnet-trace` is the simplest, but PerfView gives richer CPU analysis. Since they have admin access and it's Windows, PerfView is the gold standard for CPU investigation.\n\nActually, for CPU specifically, `dotnet-trace` with the cpu-sampling profile or PerfView are both great. Let me give a concise recommendation.","outputTokens":447,"requestId":"9430:25127A:17B5E9E:1AFC932:69E81DCD"},"id":"5d5bfd62-ec2e-4288-988a-95f00451be1b","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:01:12.878Z","parentId":"4c9a1388-1ac6-4b9c-b301-96d84d486083"}
